    "html": "<p>Markets are forward-looking, but investors are not free from the past. Institutions, political memories, industrial structures, and social expectations all limit what a market can imagine as plausible.</p>\n<p>History is useful when it is treated as a discipline of context. It should not become an analogy machine where every new event is forced into an old template. The point is not to say &quot;this is 1970s inflation&quot; or &quot;this is another Asian financial crisis.&quot; The point is to ask which constraints, incentives, and policy memories are still alive.</p>\n<p>For macro work, this matters because prices often move before the narrative becomes coherent. Historical context helps separate three things: what is genuinely new, what is a familiar institutional reaction, and what is only a market story looking for authority.</p>\n<p>That is why this site keeps history, politics, and social economics close to market sources. They do not replace the tape. They make the tape more legible.</p>\n"
